<h2>Chapter 1: Description of Data</h2>

<h3>Introduction to Data</h3>
<p>Data are raw facts and figures collected for analysis. Statistical methods help summarize and interpret data meaningfully.</p>

<h3>Types of Variables</h3>
<p>Variables are classified as qualitative (categorical) and quantitative (discrete or continuous).</p>

<h3>Mean & Weighted Mean</h3>
<p>The mean is the average value. Weighted mean assigns importance to values using weights.</p>

<h3>Median & Mode</h3>
<p>Median is the middle value; mode is the most frequent observation.</p>

<h3>Quartiles</h3>
<p>Quartiles divide data into four equal parts, helping understand data spread.</p>

<h3>Variance</h3>
<p>Variance measures how far data values spread from the mean.</p>

<h3>Coefficient of Variation</h3>
<p>It compares variability relative to the mean and is expressed as a percentage.</p>

<h3>Skewness</h3>
<p>Skewness shows asymmetry in data distribution: positive, negative, or symmetric.</p>

<h3>Histogram</h3>
<p>A histogram visually represents frequency distribution using bars.</p>

<h3>Box Plot</h3>
<p>Box plots summarize data using quartiles and identify outliers.</p>

